    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.23-25_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">23</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Greybull, Wyo.
                        Nov. 7, 1957
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine><hi rend="caps">J.G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>In a recent issue of the Saturday Evening Post in the 'Letters to the Editor' <unclear>department</unclear> your name caught my eye and in reading your comment I was surprised to find you to be the same man I once knew in Bancroft. I especially remember you as Poet-Laureate of the state and for your 'Song of Hugh Glass' which we studied in English Literature.</p>
                
                <p>My name is William <hi rend="caps">K.</hi> Schmoldt. My father was a Rural Letter Carrier out of Bancroft, Post Office along with Brey &amp; Copple. (Otto <hi rend="caps">A.</hi> Schmoldt) I came to Wyoming in 1932 but don't recall if you were still a resident of Bancroft at that time as such I remember you very well but cant recall your wife or children. I'm sure you had a boy &amp; a girl that were in school in the grades when I was in High School.</p>
                
                <p>I was born in 1912. I am on a ranch 17 miles west of Greybull &amp; am also employed as a Bus driver for a School District in that town I have in
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.23-25_0002"/>
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">24</fw>
                
                    the last five years gone thru Columbia, three different times, taking factory delieveries on new units to be used in our transportation system. Had I known that your residence was there I should have been pleased to look you up.</p>
                
                <p>If you this letter reaches you, will you please drop me a line telling me about yourself and family. In thinking about you, the thought that automatically or perhaps subconciously comes me is this: Genius is never recognized in its immediate surroundings.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours</salute>
                    <signed><unclear>Wm.</unclear> K. Schmoldt</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
